            <!-- Dehydration checklist -->
            <div class="card">
                <h2 style="font-size: 1.125rem; font-weight: 700; color: #fff; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Signs of Dehydration</h2>
                <p style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 1rem;">If you notice several of these symptoms, increase your water intake and consult a doctor if they persist.</p>
                <ul class="checklist">
                    <li><span class="check-icon">!</span> <div><strong>Dark yellow or amber urine</strong> — Pale straw color indicates proper hydration</div></li>
                    <li><span class="check-icon">!</span> <div><strong>Dry mouth and lips</strong> — Saliva production decreases when dehydrated</div></li>
                    <li><span class="check-icon">!</span> <div><strong>Fatigue and low energy</strong> — Even 1-2% dehydration impairs cognitive and physical performance</div></li>
                    <li><span class="check-icon">!</span> <div><strong>Headaches</strong> — Dehydration causes brain tissue to temporarily shrink</div></li>
                    <li><span class="check-icon">!</span> <div><strong>Dizziness or lightheadedness</strong> — Blood volume drops when you're dehydrated</div></li>
                    <li><span class="check-icon">!</span> <div><strong>Infrequent urination</strong> — Healthy adults urinate 6-8 times per day</div></li>
                    <li><span class="check-icon">!</span> <div><strong>Dry skin that doesn't bounce back</strong> — Skin turgor test: pinch skin on back of hand</div></li>
                    <li><span class="check-icon">!</span> <div><strong>Muscle cramps</strong> — Electrolyte imbalance from fluid loss affects muscle function</div></li>
                    <li><span class="check-icon">!</span> <div><strong>Rapid heartbeat</strong> — Heart works harder to maintain blood pressure when dehydrated</div></li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <!-- SEO Content -->
            <div class="seo-content">
                <h2>How Much Water Should You Drink a Day?</h2>
                <p>The amount of water you need depends on several factors including your body weight, physical activity, climate, and overall health. While the common advice is to drink "8 glasses a day," this one-size-fits-all approach doesn't account for individual differences. Our water intake calculator provides a personalized recommendation based on your specific circumstances.</p>

                <h3>How the Calculator Works</h3>
                <p>The baseline calculation uses your body weight as the primary factor. A commonly used formula recommends approximately 35 ml of water per kilogram of body weight (or about 0.5 oz per pound). This baseline is then adjusted for activity level, climate, and special conditions like pregnancy or breastfeeding.</p>

                <h3>Water Intake by Weight</h3>
                <p>Your body weight is the single most important factor in determining water needs. A 200-pound person needs significantly more water than a 120-pound person. Larger bodies have more cells to hydrate, greater blood volume to maintain, and higher metabolic rates that produce more waste products requiring dilution.</p>

                <h3>Activity Level and Hydration</h3>
                <p>Exercise increases water needs substantially. During physical activity, you lose water through sweat — anywhere from 0.5 to 2 liters per hour depending on intensity, duration, and environmental conditions. The American College of Sports Medicine recommends drinking water before, during, and after exercise to prevent dehydration.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Before exercise:</strong> 17-20 oz (500-600 ml), 2-3 hours before</li>
                    <li><strong>During exercise:</strong> 7-10 oz (200-300 ml) every 10-20 minutes</li>
                    <li><strong>After exercise:</strong> 16-24 oz (470-710 ml) per pound of body weight lost</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Climate and Water Needs</h3>
                <p>Environmental conditions significantly affect your hydration needs. In hot, humid climates, you sweat more to cool your body. In hot, dry climates, sweat evaporates quickly — you may not realize how much fluid you're losing. Even cold weather increases water needs because dry air and increased respiratory water loss contribute to dehydration.</p>

                <h3>Benefits of Proper Hydration</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Improved cognitive function:</strong> Even mild dehydration (1-2%) impairs concentration, memory, and mood</li>
                    <li><strong>Better physical performance:</strong> Dehydration reduces endurance, strength, and power output</li>
                    <li><strong>Healthy digestion:</strong> Water helps break down food and prevents constipation</li>
                    <li><strong>Kidney function:</strong> Adequate hydration helps kidneys filter waste and reduces kidney stone risk</li>
                    <li><strong>Skin health:</strong> Proper hydration supports skin elasticity and appearance</li>
                    <li><strong>Temperature regulation:</strong> Water is essential for sweating and maintaining body temperature</li>
                    <li><strong>Joint lubrication:</strong> Synovial fluid, which cushions joints, requires adequate hydration</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <div class="seo-content">
                <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
                <div class="card" style="padding: 0 1.5rem;">
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                            How much water should I drink a day?
                            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
                        </button>
                        <div class="faq-answer">The general recommendation is about 3.7 liters (125 oz) for men and 2.7 liters (91 oz) for women from all sources including food. However, your ideal intake depends on your weight, activity level, climate, and health status. Use our calculator above for a personalized recommendation.</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                            Does coffee count toward my daily water intake?
                            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
                        </button>
                        <div class="faq-answer">Yes, coffee and tea do contribute to your daily fluid intake. While caffeine has a mild diuretic effect, the net hydration from coffee is still positive. However, very high caffeine intake (over 400mg/day) may slightly increase your water needs.</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                            Can you drink too much water?
                            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
                        </button>
                        <div class="faq-answer">Yes. Overhydration (hyponatremia) occurs when you drink so much water that sodium levels in your blood become dangerously low. This is rare but can happen during extreme exercise. A general guideline is to not exceed 1 liter per hour.</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                            How do I know if I'm drinking enough water?
                            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
                        </button>
                        <div class="faq-answer">The simplest indicator is urine color. Pale straw or light yellow means you're well-hydrated. Dark yellow or amber suggests dehydration. Other signs of adequate hydration include rarely feeling thirsty, having moist lips, and producing at least 6-8 cups of urine per day.</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                            Should I drink more water when exercising?
                            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
                        </button>
                        <div class="faq-answer">Yes. The American College of Sports Medicine recommends drinking 17-20 oz (500-600 ml) 2-3 hours before exercise, 7-10 oz (200-300 ml) every 10-20 minutes during exercise, and 16-24 oz (470-710 ml) for every pound of body weight lost after exercise.</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                            Does water intake help with weight loss?
                            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
                        </button>
                        <div class="faq-answer">Research suggests that drinking water can support weight loss. A study found that drinking 500 ml of water increased metabolic rate by 30% for about 30-40 minutes. Drinking water before meals can also reduce calorie intake by 75-90 calories per meal.</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
                        <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
                            How much extra water should I drink in hot weather?
                            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"/></svg>
                        </button>
                        <div class="faq-answer">In hot or humid climates, you should increase your water intake by 1.5-2.5 additional cups (12-20 oz) per day. If you're exercising in the heat, you may need even more. In dry climates, you also lose more water through respiration, so increase intake by 1-2 cups.</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

